231
00:13:58,364 --> 00:14:00,514
We wouldn't make much money.

232
00:14:00,604 --> 00:14:03,323
-We tell a good tale, though.
-Oh, yeah.

233
00:14:04,004 --> 00:14:05,278
Oh!

234
00:14:05,604 --> 00:14:09,597
At long last, our fortunes change,
but it's not cod.

235
00:14:09,684 --> 00:14:11,117
l've got some mackerel.

236
00:14:11,204 --> 00:14:12,319
Whoa!

237
00:14:14,044 --> 00:14:15,636
(WHOOPlNG)

238
00:14:18,404 --> 00:14:21,282
RALPH: Holy mackerel,
them are the big ones!

239
00:14:21,404 --> 00:14:23,235
lt's mackerel-o-rama.

240
00:14:24,524 --> 00:14:26,242
lt's funny, we get nothing for ages,

241
00:14:26,324 --> 00:14:29,680
and now we can't put the hooks
back in quick enough.

242
00:14:30,284 --> 00:14:32,320
We did catch one cod, by the way,

243
00:14:32,404 --> 00:14:35,601
but he was such a wee tiddler,
we threw him back.

244
00:14:36,404 --> 00:14:40,238
RALPH: That's one of our codfish,
but he will grow, hopefully.

245
00:14:40,764 --> 00:14:43,324
It's so sad that as the cod fishing has gone,

246
00:14:43,404 --> 00:14:47,079
guys like Bobby and Ralph have
become a dying breed of men.

247
00:14:47,244 --> 00:14:51,203
A way of life that brought
so many people here, just wiped out.

248
00:14:56,004 --> 00:14:59,963
The old fishing livelihood may be gone,
but next, I'm heading north

249
00:15:00,044 --> 00:15:04,640
to where some surprising old country
customs are very much alive and kicking.

250
00:15:12,524 --> 00:15:15,880
So where do you think you might be?
Oban? lnverness?

251
00:15:16,284 --> 00:15:18,639
Aberdeenshire? Mallaig?

252
00:15:19,724 --> 00:15:21,237
We're in New Brunswick.

253
00:15:21,364 --> 00:15:24,242
Since 1 753, people have been coming here
from Scotland,

254
00:15:24,324 --> 00:15:25,962
since the Highland Clearances, really.

255
00:15:26,044 --> 00:15:30,356
And they tend to cling to the culture
of what they see as the culture.

256
00:15:30,844 --> 00:15:33,756
Personally, l have mixed feelings about it.

257
00:15:33,964 --> 00:15:35,602
You have a big head?

258
00:15:35,684 --> 00:15:37,037
That's not bad.

259
00:15:37,124 --> 00:15:38,682
-Oh, my God.
-Oh, that's fabulous.

260
00:15:38,764 --> 00:15:40,800
Can l have a picture with you
and that hat on?

261
00:15:40,884 --> 00:15:42,317
No. How dare you? Leave me alone.

262
00:15:42,404 --> 00:15:43,757
(LAUGHlNG)

263
00:15:44,884 --> 00:15:48,513
I think it's a New World thing,
a need for something old.

264
00:15:48,644 --> 00:15:51,556
And they seem to assume
that old means good.

265
00:15:52,804 --> 00:15:55,716
When l was a wee boy,
not only didn't we wear kilts,

266
00:15:55,804 --> 00:15:57,999
we frowned on people who did.

267
00:15:58,284 --> 00:16:01,196
We used to shout, ''Kilty, kilty, cold bum!''

268
00:16:01,604 --> 00:16:06,280
And to this day,
l am wary of people who wear kilts.

269
00:16:09,164 --> 00:16:12,474
But then there are bits of Scottish culture
I just love,

270
00:16:12,564 --> 00:16:16,034
and it's hard for me not to get carried away
by it all.

271
00:16:16,404 --> 00:16:18,360
This is the real thing.

272
00:16:20,804 --> 00:16:23,796
lt's poetry. lt's wordless poetry.

273
00:16:25,724 --> 00:16:29,034
The band of Scots that landed here
has clung on to its Highland traditions

274
00:16:29,124 --> 00:16:31,433
and kept them remarkably intact.

275
00:16:33,164 --> 00:16:37,043
This sport shows you how boring life was
in Highland villages.

