288
00:17:21,164 --> 00:17:23,473
When we get here,
we get amongst these people,

289
00:17:23,564 --> 00:17:26,476
and we wear the kilt and we hear bagpipes,
something...

290
00:17:26,564 --> 00:17:29,522
All the worries of life go away.
lt just makes us feel good.

291
00:17:29,604 --> 00:17:30,798
l can understand that.

292
00:17:30,884 --> 00:17:34,081
Most of these people here aren't
really working to be Scottish.

293
00:17:34,164 --> 00:17:37,236
-They're just out enjoying being Scottish.
-They're just enjoying themselves.

294
00:17:37,324 --> 00:17:40,157
l've got nothing against that whatsoever.

295
00:17:42,284 --> 00:17:46,835
l don't know if this is the direction
l would have gone in, if l was an immigrant.

296
00:17:47,204 --> 00:17:51,163
In one way I find it refreshing, in another way
I find it kind of very mysterious.

297
00:17:51,244 --> 00:17:54,236
I find myself being swung towards
their way of thinking.

298
00:17:54,964 --> 00:17:57,239
But then again, I was always easily led.

299
00:17:57,484 --> 00:17:59,236
l think you can tell.

300
00:17:59,444 --> 00:18:03,119
Direct from Scotland, we have a visitor,
Mr Billy Connolly.

301
00:18:06,324 --> 00:18:10,397
And when the massed bands strike up,
something stirs in me.

302
00:18:13,924 --> 00:18:18,156
No matter how much l try not to like this,
l love it.

303
00:18:18,684 --> 00:18:22,120
l go all wobbly inside. l can't help it.

304
00:18:22,204 --> 00:18:26,641
When the drums and pipes go, it's just...
l'm putty in their hands.

305
00:18:29,604 --> 00:18:32,914
You can't refuse an occasion
to make Scottish cool.

306
00:18:33,324 --> 00:18:35,394
And it really is pretty nifty.

307
00:18:39,084 --> 00:18:42,440
As I hit the road,
with the music still ringing in my ears,

308
00:18:42,524 --> 00:18:46,676
I think I can see why all this Scottishness
is so strong over here.

309
00:18:51,164 --> 00:18:55,157
l think it's the size of the place,
and the amount of wilderness

310
00:18:55,484 --> 00:18:58,317
that makes them so keen on their culture.

311
00:18:58,644 --> 00:19:02,114
Anything that you can grab
that makes you feel at home

312
00:19:02,564 --> 00:19:04,759
must bring you great solace.

313
00:19:06,844 --> 00:19:09,722
I've driven through Nova Scotia
to Cape Breton Island,

314
00:19:09,804 --> 00:19:12,557
where I'm heading towards a town
called Cheticamp,

315
00:19:12,644 --> 00:19:16,842
where I'm going to meet a different group of
settlers that have made their colourful mark.

316
00:19:16,924 --> 00:19:20,633
Before this was ever Nova Scotia,
it was called New France.

317
00:19:20,884 --> 00:19:23,239
And hereabouts,
the people still speak French.

318
00:19:23,324 --> 00:19:27,954
They call themselves Acadians, descendants
of 17th-century French colonists.

319
00:19:32,164 --> 00:19:35,873
There's a distinctly odd feel to this place,
and I like it.

320
00:19:36,604 --> 00:19:40,074
What l'm looking forward to,
there's a scarecrow maker.

321
00:19:40,204 --> 00:19:43,594
l've never met a scarecrow maker before.
l never thought there were such things.

322
00:19:43,684 --> 00:19:47,199
l thought farmers just hammered them
together from brushes and old clothes.

323
00:19:47,524 --> 00:19:49,958
This should be a bit interesting.

324
00:19:50,924 --> 00:19:52,880
Oh, God, it's quite scary!

325
00:19:54,084 --> 00:19:57,235
Look at that line at the back.
That is so weird.

326
00:19:58,924 --> 00:20:00,118
Oh, l like this.

327
00:20:00,204 --> 00:20:04,163
There's a funky, weird edge to this
that l'm beginning to like.

328
00:20:06,284 --> 00:20:07,922
Stone the crows.

329
00:20:10,284 --> 00:20:12,081
lt's... l can't explain it to you.

330
00:20:12,164 --> 00:20:15,952
l think it's because they're absolute life-size
with real clothes on.

331
00:20:16,044 --> 00:20:19,514
There's a definite Village of the Damned
feel about it.

332
00:20:20,404 --> 00:20:25,762
l think it's this thing. l think it's this pose.
lt's like some kind of satanic rite.

333
00:20:27,164 --> 00:20:30,361
Oh, God, Margaret Thatcher's here,
of all people.

334
00:20:31,404 --> 00:20:33,838
lt gets more bizarre by the yard.

335
00:20:35,764 --> 00:20:37,561
l love these things.

336
00:20:40,004 --> 00:20:42,359
The other visitors, they're just like me.

337
00:20:42,444 --> 00:20:46,073
People are, you know...
The average expression is...

338
00:20:47,044 --> 00:20:49,512
What the fudd is this?

339
00:20:50,404 --> 00:20:54,158
lsn't it odd? l mean,
l don't know if you can feel it up the lens.

340
00:20:54,244 --> 00:20:59,193
lt's like getting into a graveyard and finding
all the people standing, l'm telling you.

341
00:20:59,284 --> 00:21:02,196
I was wondering what kind of oddball
was behind all this,

342
00:21:02,284 --> 00:21:05,082
when Chester shows up,
and he's a true delight.

343
00:21:05,164 --> 00:21:07,200
-How are you?
-How do you do? Billy Connolly.

344
00:21:07,284 --> 00:21:09,240
-Are you Chester Delaney?
